00:16:02,480 --> 00:16:04,300
Did the police find Conrad's body yet?

260
00:16:04,640 --> 00:16:08,440
No, they've labeled him missing and they've gone out looking for him.

261
00:16:09,060 --> 00:16:11,240
- I knew we shouldn't have hidden the body in the forest.

262
00:16:11,620 --> 00:16:13,800
We should have just gone straight to the police.

263
00:16:14,020 --> 00:16:15,900
- What's the use of saying that now?

264
00:16:16,160 --> 00:16:16,980
I think you're forgetting,

265
00:16:17,080 --> 00:16:18,460
you're the one who thought I'd shot him.

266
00:16:18,800 --> 00:16:19,220
Damn it!

267
00:16:19,600 --> 00:16:21,480
This is what we get for winning the lottery.

268
00:16:22,020 --> 00:16:23,360
- I keep on telling you,

269
00:16:23,600 --> 00:16:25,340
you shouldn't have bought these horrible things.

270
00:16:32,940 --> 00:16:33,840
- No use waiting.

271
00:16:34,300 --> 00:16:35,700
There won't be any trains.

272
00:16:35,700 --> 00:16:38,840
The Elgar River has flooded out the railway bridge.

273
00:16:39,260 --> 00:16:41,580
All roads are closed due to the flooding as well.

274
00:16:44,140 --> 00:16:45,320
A solitary island.

275
00:16:46,220 --> 00:16:47,680
The worst possible scenario.

276
00:16:49,040 --> 00:16:50,480
Klaus Poppe, is it?

277
00:16:50,800 --> 00:16:52,060
Do you know about him?

278
00:16:52,320 --> 00:16:53,660
Jakob Feuerbach.

279
00:16:54,160 --> 00:16:56,260
And Emil Scherbeck.

280
00:16:59,780 --> 00:17:03,840
Do you know about them? Because I think they and Poppe are the same man.

281
00:17:05,700 --> 00:17:09,900
matter in art are different in each. When you've seen as much as I have, you notice

282
00:17:09,900 --> 00:17:14,580
certain things. However, I couldn't tell you why he would use so many pen names, though.

283
00:17:14,960 --> 00:17:21,140
His art is good. But for some reason, I really can't appreciate his work. There are plenty

284
00:17:21,140 --> 00:17:27,420
of picture books around the world that have gloomy stories. But somehow, his art... different.

285
00:17:27,840 --> 00:17:33,200
- How so? What do you mean? - Hmm. I guess you could say they're brimming

286
00:17:33,200 --> 00:17:46,440
with malice. Before I forget, there's another one. This storybook from Helmuth Foss, published

287
00:17:46,440 --> 00:17:53,120
in Germany in 1989. It's hard to get because there were so few printed, but I believe he

288
00:17:53,120 --> 00:18:00,580
is also the same man as Klaus Poppe. How can you be sure about that? As I said, I'm able

289
00:18:00,580 --> 00:18:04,880
to tell these things. When you do it long enough, you know. No matter how he changes

290
00:18:04,880 --> 00:18:09,680
his art, there are little things that always remain the same. This story's content is

291
00:18:09,680 --> 00:18:14,860
an about-face from the others. A thief sneaks into a quiet village in the mountains. He

292
00:18:14,860 --> 00:18:19,500
plans to make off with a good sum of money from the villagers. But as he interacts with

293
00:18:19,500 --> 00:18:24,000
the people of the village, he forgets how to steal, and eventually he ends up leading

294
00:18:24,000 --> 00:18:30,580
a quiet life, helping the village folks. The title is "The Peaceful House."

295
00:18:30,580 --> 00:18:35,960
Pope's usual unpleasant aftertaste is gone. However, his artwork takes quite a

296
00:18:35,960 --> 00:18:39,720
turn for the worse. A bit of a strange thing happened. It

297
00:18:39,720 --> 00:18:42,500
seems his story got better, but he forgot how to draw.

298
00:18:43,020 --> 00:18:46,380
It's as if... as if he lost his purpose.

299
00:18:47,840 --> 00:18:51,380
A peaceful home. A village in the mountains.

300
00:18:53,280 --> 00:18:57,860
"Our home is a small town in southern Germany, surrounded by many mountains."

301
00:18:59,940 --> 00:19:01,140
"A map."

302
00:19:01,140 --> 00:19:01,960
"Hm?"

303
00:19:01,960 --> 00:19:06,220
"Do you happen to have a map of southern Germany?"

304
00:19:07,460 --> 00:19:09,340
"So what are you looking for?"

305
00:19:09,340 --> 00:19:12,120
"A small town surrounded by many mountains.

306
00:19:13,580 --> 00:19:14,540
There it is."

307
00:19:15,500 --> 00:19:16,100
"Hm."

308
00:19:18,480 --> 00:19:19,080
"Ruhenheim."

309
00:19:19,080 --> 00:19:20,260
(dramatic music)

310
00:19:25,580 --> 00:19:27,960
- Holy cow, it's a monsoon out there.

311
00:19:29,000 --> 00:19:30,200
- So how did it go?

312
00:19:30,580 --> 00:19:33,060
Were you able to locate Conrad in all that rain?

313
00:19:33,460 --> 00:19:34,920
- Nope, not a trace.

314
00:19:35,300 --> 00:19:37,060
My partners are still looking around,

315
00:19:37,400 --> 00:19:40,360
but given the way it's been raining all afternoon,

316
00:19:41,120 --> 00:19:42,880
the overflowing river's taking the trains

317
00:19:42,880 --> 00:19:44,000
and roads out of service.

318
00:19:44,880 --> 00:19:47,160
I know you must be concerned about your friend.

319
00:19:49,180 --> 00:19:51,700
I mean, normally, this place is just so peaceful.

320
00:19:52,180 --> 00:19:54,880
But then Conrad goes missing, and the next thing you know,

321
00:19:54,980 --> 00:19:56,700
Mrs. Hillman's dog is shot dead.

322
00:19:57,580 --> 00:19:59,340
Poor Mrs. Hillman is so distraught,

323
00:19:59,360 --> 00:20:00,920
she's confined to her bed with grief.

324
00:20:02,080 --> 00:20:03,360
And that's not all.

325
00:20:03,460 --> 00:20:06,300
Mr. Kemnar was attacked leaving the pub last night.

326
00:20:06,880 --> 00:20:08,620
I hear his condition is serious.

327
00:20:09,440 --> 00:20:10,840
And the perp got away.

328
00:20:10,940 --> 00:20:11,700
We got nothing.

329
00:20:12,400 --> 00:20:14,760
If he should actually die as a result of those injuries,

330
00:20:14,940 --> 00:20:16,980
it will be this town's first ever murder.

331
00:20:16,980 --> 00:20:20,500
Things are falling apart and because of this rain we can't get back up.

332
00:20:20,860 --> 00:20:22,780
What are we supposed to do with only a few people?

333
00:20:24,160 --> 00:20:26,340
It must be the work of outsiders.

334
00:20:26,800 --> 00:20:29,280
Crime in this town is basically non-existent.

335
00:20:29,700 --> 00:20:31,000
It's gotta be them, right?

336
00:20:31,340 --> 00:20:33,500
We're outsiders. Are you locking us up?

337
00:20:37,060 --> 00:20:39,320
No, I'm not suggesting that.

338
00:20:39,660 --> 00:20:41,360
This rain is fierce.

339
00:20:41,780 --> 00:20:44,580
I can hardly go outside in my wheelchair in this weather.

340
00:20:48,660 --> 00:20:52,720
Well, I'd better go patrol one more time and then catch up with my partners.

341
00:20:53,060 --> 00:20:54,280
Be careful out there.

342
00:21:02,820 --> 00:21:06,540
Your husband's shoes are remarkably muddy and wet.

343
00:21:07,260 --> 00:21:10,480
As if he'd been spending time walking around in the rain.

344
00:21:11,260 --> 00:21:13,500
I'd like to use your phone, if I may.

345
00:21:26,700 --> 00:21:27,180
Huh?

346
00:21:29,960 --> 00:21:31,420
Uh, it's just that lush.

347
00:21:32,260 --> 00:21:34,980
Can't be him. He can't do anything at all.

348
00:21:41,000 --> 00:21:41,740
[SUSPENSEFUL MUSIC]

349
00:21:42,460 --> 00:21:42,820
Hm?

350
00:21:45,240 --> 00:21:46,140
[SUSPENSEFUL MUSIC]

351
00:21:47,600 --> 00:21:48,620
What's wrong?

352
00:21:49,100 --> 00:21:50,000
Are you out of gas?

353
00:21:50,960 --> 00:21:52,080
Is it leaking oil?

354
00:21:54,000 --> 00:21:55,400
I could radio for a mechanic.

355
00:21:56,980 --> 00:21:57,220
[SUSPENSEFUL MUSIC]

356
00:21:57,220 --> 00:21:57,240
Hm?

357
00:21:58,180 --> 00:21:59,620
[SUSPENSEFUL MUSIC]

358
00:22:00,100 --> 00:22:00,560
[GUNSHOT]

359
00:22:02,000 --> 00:22:02,720
[SUSPENSEFUL MUSIC]

360
00:22:04,260 --> 00:22:05,560
That was another gunshot.

361
00:22:07,360 --> 00:22:08,080
[SUSPENSEFUL MUSIC]

362
00:22:10,920 --> 00:22:13,220
All the phone lines must be down.

363
00:22:16,900 --> 00:22:20,040
Is it too late for us to prevent the bloodshed around the corner?

